{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778536876,"nonce":"OLymiXwHpkg0ogRD4PUfj7oS88Y=","message":"## Correction — `nn_hidden_derivative = 1e2` was 1e5× the Shahbazi-effective weight\n\nIn this matrix's headline framing, the smoothness penalty was described as \"Shahbazi-scale\" (`nn_hidden_derivative = 1e2`). On closer reading of Shahbazi 2025 Eq. 1:\n\n```\nL_h^t = h_t^T h_t + 10^2 · ḣ_t^T ḣ_t       (multiplied by 1e-5 in L_t)\n```\n\nThe effective weight on the derivative term is `1e-5 × 1e2 = 1e-3`, NOT `1e2`. This matrix actually ran with `1e2` applied directly to `ḣ_t^T ḣ_t`, which is **1e5× larger** than Shahbazi's effective weight.\n\n**Implication**: the dramatic effects in cells 3 and 4 (variance collapse to CV ≈ 0.006, peak velocity ~2× control, hold drift +80% in cell 3 alone) should be interpreted as showing what aggressive smoothness does, NOT as a Shahbazi-faithful replication. The qualitative finding (\"smoothness is the dominant variance-collapse lever\") still holds; the weight scale at which we observed it is non-literature.\n\nSubsequent lit-replication matrix `f47abb1` uses `nn_hidden_derivative = 1e-3` for proper Shahbazi alignment.","files":null}]}